qas.question: WHat were nobles named in german language?
What were the nobles named in lithuanian?
What were the higher nobility named?
The kunigai were subordinate to who?
What word is used to denominate nobility?

context: In Lithuania Propria and in Samogitia prior to the creation of the Kingdom of Lithuania by Mindaugas, nobles were named <a0_0>die beste leuten<a0_0/> in sources that were written in German language. In the Lithuanian language nobles were named <a1_0>ponai<a1_0/>. The higher nobility were named '<a2_0>kunigai' or 'kunigaikščiai'<a2_0/> (dukes)—i.e., loanword from Scandinavic konung. They were the established local leaders and warlords. During the development of the state they gradually became subordinated to higher dukes, and later to the <a3_0>King of Lithuania.<a3_0/> Because of expansion of Lithuanian duchy into lands of Ruthenia in the mid of 14th century a new term appeared to denominate nobility bajorai—from Ruthenian (modern Ukrainian and Belarusian languages) <a4_0>бояре<a4_0/>. This word to this day is used in Lithuanian language to name nobility, not only for own, but also for nobility of other countries.
